Over the course of 5 years,
the idea is fairly similar.

00:08:33.936 --> 00:08:36.273
You're going to pay, some
part of this is going

00:08:36.273 --> 00:08:40.138
to be interest, and the remainder is going

00:08:40.138 --> 00:08:42.275
to actually be used to pay down the loan.

00:08:42.275 --> 00:08:44.063
Each month you're going to pay down

00:08:44.063 --> 00:08:45.374
a little bit more of the loan, and you're

00:08:45.374 --> 00:08:47.002
going to have to pay a
little less in interest.

00:08:47.002 --> 00:08:48.845
Make that a little bit bigger.

00:08:48.845 --> 00:08:53.262
You're going to have to pay
a little bit less interest,

00:08:53.262 --> 00:08:56.980
because you have less
remaining on your loan,

00:08:56.980 --> 00:09:02.451
but by year 5, or month 60, you
still haven't paid your loan off.

00:09:02.451 --> 00:09:07.063
Maybe the interest is right over there,

00:09:07.063 --> 00:09:08.697
and actually it'll probably
be higher than that.

00:09:08.697 --> 00:09:09.920
I don't want to be too exact,

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:13.596
but maybe your interest is
going to be right over here;

00:09:13.596 --> 00:09:18.567
and this is what you're
paying down from the loan.

00:09:18.567 --> 00:09:21.398
For a hybrid adjustable rate mortgage,

00:09:21.398 --> 00:09:23.810
after that 5 year period, the bank

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:26.135
can now change the interest rate.

00:09:26.135 --> 00:09:27.962
The interest rate is going to be dependent

00:09:27.962 --> 00:09:30.365
on some kind of underlying thing

00:09:30.365 --> 00:09:32.597
that everyone is paying attention to.

00:09:32.597 --> 00:09:36.150
That underlying thing
increases in interest.

00:09:36.150 --> 00:09:41.947
In this 5/1 ARM, it starts
off at a 3% interest.

00:09:41.947 --> 00:09:44.246
If, because of the thing that we're paying

00:09:44.246 --> 00:09:47.082
attention to, and I'll talk
more about that in a second,

00:09:47.082 --> 00:09:50.075
interest rates all of a sudden go up.

00:09:50.075 --> 00:09:52.628
Let's say they go up a
lot, then all of a sudden

00:09:52.628 --> 00:09:54.139
your payment could increase.

00:09:54.139 --> 00:09:56.576
Your payment could increase
because the general

00:09:56.576 --> 00:10:00.453
idea behind a 5/1 ARM
is that you are still

00:10:00.453 --> 00:10:03.266
going to pay it off in 30 years.

00:10:03.266 --> 00:10:07.193
They typically, I should
say, have a 30 year term.

00:10:07.193 --> 00:10:09.500
If you just stick with this loan,

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:11.370
you never try to borrow other money

00:10:11.370 --> 00:10:13.448
to replace this loan, which
is called a refinance,

00:10:13.448 --> 00:10:15.883
if you just stick with this
loan it will take you 30 years

00:10:15.883 --> 00:10:18.208
to pay it off, but after the first 5 years

00:10:18.208 --> 00:10:21.266
the amount of interest
you pay might actually

00:10:21.266 --> 00:10:24.295
change, so your payment
might actually change.

00:10:24.295 --> 00:10:28.008
If the interest rate
goes up, all of a sudden

00:10:28.008 --> 00:10:30.376
you might have to pay a lot more interest

00:10:30.376 --> 00:10:36.892
all of a sudden in month 61, or in year 6.

00:10:36.892 --> 00:10:41.554
Let me do that in, I can do that
part in that same blue color.

00:10:41.554 --> 00:10:44.662
For year 6, since this is a 5/1 ARM,

00:10:44.662 --> 00:10:47.989
they can't change the interest
rate again until year 7,

00:10:47.989 --> 00:10:50.934
so you'll pay this constant
amount until year 7.

00:10:50.934 --> 00:10:53.089
Then, they can change the rate again.

00:10:53.089 --> 00:10:54.742
There usually are some caps

00:10:54.742 --> 00:10:56.840
on how much they can
change the rate each year,

00:10:56.840 --> 00:10:58.958
or how much they can
change the rate in total;

00:10:58.958 --> 00:11:00.627
but it is a little bit riskier because

00:11:00.627 --> 00:11:02.416
you really don't know
what your payment might be

00:11:02.416 --> 00:11:05.878
in year 6, or year 7, especially
if interest rates go up a lot.

00:11:05.878 --> 00:11:08.917
Now, you might be asking what determines

00:11:08.917 --> 00:11:12.884
what that new interest rate
is in after the 5 years.

00:11:12.884 --> 00:11:15.032
They usually pick some type of index.

00:11:15.032 --> 00:11:18.113
The most typical are,
especially in the United States,

00:11:18.113 --> 00:11:22.573
treasury securities; so,
they'll look at the 10 year

00:11:22.573 --> 00:11:24.904
interest rate that
essentially the government

00:11:24.904 --> 00:11:26.634
has to pay when it borrows money,

00:11:26.634 --> 00:11:28.861
and they'll usually take
some premium over this.

00:11:28.861 --> 00:11:31.888
If the 10 year treasury is at 2%,

00:11:31.888 --> 00:11:35.039
the bank might put in your loan documents

00:11:35.039 --> 00:11:37.733
that after the initial
5 year fixed period,

00:11:37.733 --> 00:11:41.286
you will pay 10 year treasury rate plus,

00:11:41.286 --> 00:11:43.115
maybe you'll pay that plus 1%.

00:11:43.115 --> 00:11:46.548
You start off paying the 3%, that's fixed

00:11:46.548 --> 00:11:48.445
even if the treasury does
all sorts of crazy things,

00:11:48.445 --> 00:11:49.905
even if it goes up to
5%, you're just going

00:11:49.905 --> 00:11:52.778
to keep paying the 3%
for the first 5 years,

00:11:52.778 --> 00:11:56.039
but then in that 6th year, let's say that,

00:11:56.039 --> 00:11:57.646
let me write it over here,

00:11:57.646 --> 00:12:02.069
let's say that in year 6
the treasury security rate

00:12:02.069 --> 00:12:07.381
now has bumped up to 4%, then by contract,

00:12:07.381 --> 00:12:09.019
by what's in your loan document,

00:12:09.019 --> 00:12:11.554
you're going to have to pay that plus 1%.

00:12:11.554 --> 00:12:15.923
Now, your mortgage is
going to reset to have

00:12:15.923 --> 00:12:18.634
a 5% rate, have a higher rate.

00:12:18.634 --> 00:12:20.087
You might get lucky, though.

00:12:20.087 --> 00:12:22.222
Maybe the treasury rate goes down,

00:12:22.222 --> 00:12:24.818
maybe it goes to 1%,
and then your mortgage

00:12:24.818 --> 00:12:27.226
rate would actually be 1% plus 1%,

00:12:27.226 --> 00:12:29.776
so it could actually go down to 2%.

00:12:29.776 --> 00:12:32.907
But the general idea is
that's a little riskier,

00:12:32.907 --> 00:12:34.222
because you really don't know

00:12:34.222 --> 00:12:37.316
how predictable that
payment's going to be.

00:12:37.316 --> 00:12:41.966
Most times, if you look
at quoted interest rates,

00:12:41.966 --> 00:12:45.265
you'll see that the 30
year fixed rate is higher

00:12:45.265 --> 00:12:49.918
than the 15 year fixed rate, which
is higher than the adjustable rate.

00:12:49.918 --> 00:12:52.624
That's because the bank, there's a couple

00:12:52.624 --> 00:12:54.813
of different forms of risk,
but the bank is taking

00:12:54.813 --> 00:12:56.775
the least amount of risk
on the adjustable rate

00:12:56.775 --> 00:13:00.382
mortgage, and taking the most
risk on the 30 year fixed.

00:13:00.382 --> 00:13:02.687
The biggest risk here, there's
the risk that you don't

00:13:02.687 --> 00:13:04.281
pay it off; but that's
why they like to see

00:13:04.281 --> 00:13:05.860
a down payment, because they can get

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:07.466
the house back and
hopefully the house doesn't

